msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:0
msgid "**`dialect-nvvm`**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:0
msgid "GPU intrinsics -- thread indexing, warp shuffles, TMA, WGMMA"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:0
msgid "`nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x`, `nvvm.shfl_sync`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:51
msgid ""
"Without an extensible IR, we would have to either jam Rust enums into LLVM "
"IR (losing semantic information) or build separate IR frameworks for each "
"level of the pipeline. MLIR lets us define all three as dialects in a single "
"system and lower between them with well-typed passes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:56
msgid "Enter pliron"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:58
msgid ""
"MLIR's dialect-and-lowering model is the right abstraction for cuda-oxide: "
"keep high-level semantics in the IR while progressively lowering toward code "
"the GPU backend can consume. The question is implementation fit. Upstream "
"MLIR is part of the LLVM C++ ecosystem, while cuda-oxide is a Rust compiler "
"project built around Rust crates, Rust types, and Cargo workflows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:64
msgid ""
"[Pliron](https://github.com/vaivaswatha/pliron) is an MLIR-inspired "
"extensible compiler IR framework written in **pure Rust**. It follows the "
"same conceptual model -- operations, regions, basic blocks, types, "
"attributes, dialects, passes -- while fitting naturally into a Rust-native "
"compiler stack."
msgstr ""

