"For cuda-oxide, this means the entire compiler -- from MIR import to LLVM IR "
"export -- stays within the same Rust build and debugging environment as the "
"rest of the project. Pliron gives us the extensible IR structure we need "
"without moving the compiler out of the Rust ecosystem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:83
msgid "Core data structures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:85
msgid ""
"Pliron's IR is built from a handful of core types. Understanding these is "
"the key to reading (and writing) dialect code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:88
msgid "Context"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:90
msgid ""
"The `Context` is the central data structure that owns *all* IR data -- "
"operations, basic blocks, regions, types, attributes, and dialect "
"registrations. Think of it as the arena allocator for your entire "
"compilation unit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:94
msgid ""
"// Simplified -- the real Context has more fields\n"
"pub struct Context {\n"
"    operations: SlotMap<Ptr<Operation>, Operation>,\n"
"    basic_blocks: SlotMap<Ptr<BasicBlock>, BasicBlock>,\n"
"    regions: SlotMap<Ptr<Region>, Region>,\n"
"    dialects: HashMap<DialectName, Dialect>,\n"
"    type_store: TypeStore,     // uniqued (deduplicated) types\n"
"    // Attributes are not stored centrally -- see \"Types and attributes\" "
"below.\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:106
msgid ""
"Pliron uses **generational arenas** (from the `slotmap` crate) instead of "
"`Box`-allocated heap nodes. This gives you:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:109
msgid ""
"**O(1) insert and remove** -- no tree rebalancing, no linked-list traversal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:110
msgid ""
"**Stable indices** -- inserting or removing an element does not invalidate "
"other indices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:112
msgid ""
"**Generational versioning** -- each slot carries a generation counter. If "
"you delete an operation and the slot gets reused, any old reference will "
"have a stale generation and fail at runtime instead of silently reading "
"garbage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:116
msgid ""
"Every piece of IR is stored inside the Context. You never hold a direct "
"`&mut Operation` across function boundaries -- you hold a `Ptr<Operation>` "
"and deref it through the Context when needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:120
msgid "Operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:122
msgid ""
"An **operation** is a single node in the IR graph. It has operands (inputs), "
"results (outputs), attributes (compile-time metadata), and optionally "
"regions (nested structure for things like function bodies and loop nests)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:126
msgid ""
"Every operation belongs to a dialect. The naming convention is `dialect_name."
"op_name`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:129
msgid ""
"#[pliron_op(name = \"mir.func\", dialect = \"mir\")]\n"
"pub struct MirFuncOp;\n"
"\n"
"#[pliron_op(name = \"nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x\", dialect = \"nvvm\")]\n"
"pub struct ReadPtxSregTidXOp;\n"
"\n"
"#[pliron_op(name = \"llvm.add\", dialect = \"llvm\")]\n"
"pub struct AddOp;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:140
msgid ""
"The `#[pliron_op(...)]` proc macro (from `pliron-derive`) generates the "
"boilerplate for registering the operation with its dialect, assigning it an "
"opcode, and wiring up the `Op` trait. You define the operation's semantics "
"by implementing `Verify`, `Printable`, and `Parsable`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:145
msgid "Types and attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:147
msgid ""
"**Types** represent data types in the IR. Pliron's built-in dialect provides "
"integers (`i1`, `i32`, `i64`) and floats (`f32`, `f64`). cuda-oxide's MIR "
"dialect extends these with Rust-specific types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:151
msgid ""
"#[pliron_type(name = \"mir.tuple\", dialect = \"mir\")]\n"
"pub struct MirTupleType {\n"
"    pub types: Vec<Ptr<TypeObj>>,\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[pliron_type(name = \"mir.slice\", dialect = \"mir\")]\n"
"pub struct MirSliceType {\n"
"    pub element_ty: Ptr<TypeObj>,\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[pliron_type(name = \"mir.enum\", dialect = \"mir\")]\n"
"pub struct MirEnumType {\n"
"    pub name: String,\n"
"    pub discriminant_ty: Ptr<TypeObj>,\n"
"    pub variant_names: Vec<String>,\n"
"    // ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:171
msgid ""
"**Attributes** attach compile-time metadata to operations -- constant "
"values, flags, predicate kinds, cast kinds, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:174
msgid "Types and attributes are stored differently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:176
msgid ""
"**Types are uniqued** (deduplicated). If you create two `MirTupleType "
"{ types: vec![i32, f32] }` instances, pliron stores only one copy and hands "
"back the same pointer. Type equality becomes a pointer comparison instead of "
"a deep structural compare."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:180
msgid ""
"**Attributes are not uniqued by default.** Each operation carries its own "
"attribute values inline. This matches how MLIR's \"properties\" work -- MLIR "
"originally uniqued attributes too, found that mutation and per-op state were "
"awkward, and introduced properties as the unstored, per-op alternative. "
"Pliron skipped that detour and started with the property-shaped design."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:187
msgid ""
"If you do want to dedup an attribute (for example, a 4 KB constant lookup "
"table that many ops reference), opt into uniquing per-attribute via the "
"`uniqued_any` utility. The pattern is to wrap the heavy payload in a "
"`UniquedKey<T>` and store the key inside the attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:192
msgid ""
"struct SomeData { /* large or expensive-to-compare payload */ }\n"
"\n"
"#[pliron_attr(name = \"...\", dialect = \"...\")]\n"
"pub struct SomeDataAttr(pub UniquedKey<SomeData>);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:199
msgid ""
"Now `SomeDataAttr` is a small handle that compares by key; the underlying "
"`SomeData` lives once in the uniquing table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:202
msgid "Ptr\\<T\\> -- safe arena references"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:204
msgid ""
"`Ptr<T>` is pliron's equivalent of a pointer into the arena. Under the hood, "
"it is composed of two fields:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:207
msgid ""
"pub struct Ptr<T> {\n"
"    index: u32,           // slot index in the arena\n"
"    version: NonZeroU32,  // generational version\n"
"    _phantom: PhantomData<T>,\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:215
msgid ""
"The **version** field is what makes this safe. When you delete an operation, "
"pliron bumps the generation counter on that slot. If someone later tries to "
"dereference an old `Ptr<Operation>` whose version no longer matches the "
"slot's current generation, the access fails instead of reading the new "
"(unrelated) occupant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:221
msgid ""
"The `PhantomData<T>` ensures type safety at compile time -- you cannot "
"accidentally use a `Ptr<Operation>` to index into the `BasicBlock` arena. "
"The compiler won't let you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:226
msgid "You interact with arena contents through the Context:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:228
msgid "`ptr.deref(ctx)` returns a shared reference (`&T`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:229
msgid "`ptr.deref_mut(ctx)` returns an exclusive reference (`&mut T`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:231
msgid ""
"This follows Rust's borrow model -- the Context is the owner, and you borrow "
"through it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:235
msgid "Def-use chains (memory-safe)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:237
msgid "In any compiler IR, you need to answer two questions constantly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:239
msgid ""
"**Use-def**: \"Where is this value defined?\" (Given a use, find the "
"definition.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:240
msgid ""
"**Def-use**: \"Where is this value used?\" (Given a definition, find all "
"uses.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:242
msgid ""
"Traditional compilers implement these chains with raw pointers and manual "
"bookkeeping. Forget to update a use-list when you delete an operation? "
"Dangling pointer. Replace a value but miss one use? Stale reference. Welcome "
"to your afternoon of debugging a segfault in `opt -O2`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:247
msgid ""
"Pliron implements def-use chains using Rust's type system. A `Value` in "
"pliron is an enum:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:250
msgid ""
"pub enum Value {\n"
"    OpResult { op: Ptr<Operation>, index: usize },\n"
"    BlockArgument { block: Ptr<BasicBlock>, index: usize },\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:257
msgid ""
"Every value is either the result of an operation or an argument to a basic "
"block. Each definition tracks the set of all its uses, and each use stores a "
"pointer back to its definition. When you call `replace_all_uses_with`, both "
"sides update automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:262
msgid "This means:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:264
msgid ""
"**No dangling references** -- removing an operation updates all use-lists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:265
msgid "**No stale uses** -- replacing a value propagates to every consumer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:266
msgid ""
"**No segfaults during IR transforms** -- the borrow checker and generational "
"arenas prevent the entire class of bugs that plague C++ compiler frameworks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:270
msgid ""
"If you are familiar with LLVM's `Value` / `Use` / `User` system, pliron's "
"design serves the same purpose. The difference is that LLVM implements it "
"with intrusive linked lists and raw `Value*` pointers, while pliron "
"implements it with arena indices and `HashSet<UseNode>`. The semantics are "
"similar, but the ownership model fits Rust IR transforms directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:277
msgid "Op interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:279
msgid ""
"Most things you want to do across an entire IR -- verify it, print it, lower "
"it to another dialect -- naturally express as \"every op that implements "
"interface `X` knows how to do `X`\". Pliron makes that pattern first-class "
"through **op interfaces**: small Rust traits, marked with `#[op_interface]`, "
"that any op (or type, or attribute) can implement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:285
msgid ""
"You define an interface like a normal Rust trait, with the `#[op_interface]` "
"attribute on top:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:288
msgid ""
"use pliron::derive::op_interface;\n"
"\n"
"#[op_interface]\n"
"pub trait MirToLlvmConversion {\n"
"    fn convert(\n"
"        &self,\n"
"        ctx: &mut Context,\n"
"        rewriter: &mut DialectConversionRewriter,\n"
"        operands_info: &OperandsInfo,\n"
"    ) -> Result<()>;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:302
msgid "Each op implements the interface with `#[op_interface_impl]`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:304
msgid ""
"use pliron::derive::op_interface_impl;\n"
"\n"
"#[op_interface_impl]\n"
"impl MirToLlvmConversion for MirAddOp {\n"
"    fn convert(\n"
"        &self,\n"
"        ctx: &mut Context,\n"
"        rewriter: &mut DialectConversionRewriter,\n"
"        operands_info: &OperandsInfo,\n"
"    ) -> Result<()> {\n"
"        // ...lower MirAddOp into one or more LLVM dialect ops...\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:320
msgid ""
"The framework then dispatches against the interface, not against a specific "
"concrete op type. A pass that lowers MIR to LLVM looks roughly like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:324
msgid ""
"// Inside DialectConversion::rewrite, for each op encountered:\n"
"if let Some(converter) = op_cast::<dyn MirToLlvmConversion>(op) {\n"
"    converter.convert(ctx, rewriter, operands_info)?;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:331
msgid ""
"If you add a new MIR op tomorrow and write its `#[op_interface_impl]`, the "
"lowering pass picks it up automatically -- no central match statement to "
"update, no enum to grow. The same pattern is used for verification "
"(`#[op_interface] trait Verify`), printing, and any other cross-cutting "
"behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:337
msgid ""
"The same `#[op_interface]` / `#[op_interface_impl]` mechanism applies to "
"types and attributes too: a type can implement `dyn MemorySemantics`, a "
"constant attribute can implement `dyn TypedAttr`, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:342
msgid ""
"Under the hood, `op_cast` is a small runtime lookup (one hash table probe) "
"that maps the op's concrete type to the interface implementation the macros "
"registered. It only fires during pass dispatch, not in the hot path of IR "
"construction. The benefit is that adding a dialect is adding a crate -- "
"never modifying a central enum or generics-tangled function signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:350
msgid "How cuda-oxide uses pliron"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:352
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide works with three dialects: it defines `dialect-mir` and `dialect-"
"nvvm` locally (each as its own crate) and consumes the LLVM dialect from the "
"upstream `pliron-llvm` crate. Registration is automatic: every dialect, op, "
"type, and attribute linked into the binary registers itself when a `Context` "
"is created (`Context::default` runs all link-time registrations), so kernel "
"authors and pass authors never have to think about dialect setup -- "
"depending on the crate is the only thing you do."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:360
msgid "dialect-mir -- Rust semantics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:362
msgid ""
"`dialect-mir` captures Rust's mid-level IR as pliron operations, preserving "
"semantic information that would be lost if we lowered directly to LLVM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:365
msgid ""
"**Function definition**: `MirFuncOp` -- entry point for each device "
"function, with typed block arguments matching the Rust function signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:367
msgid ""
"**Arithmetic and comparison**: checked and unchecked binary ops (`mir.add`, "
"`mir.sub`, `mir.eq`, `mir.lt`, ...) that preserve Rust's overflow semantics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:369
msgid ""
"**Aggregate types**: `MirTupleType`, `MirStructType`, `MirEnumType`, "
"`MirSliceType`, `MirArrayType` -- first-class Rust compound types with "
"operations like `mir.extract_field` and `mir.get_discriminant`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:372
msgid ""
"**Memory and control flow**: `mir.load`, `mir.store`, `mir.ref`, `mir.goto`, "
"`mir.cond_br`, `mir.return` -- with GPU address-space tracking (`global`, "
"`shared`, `local`, `tmem`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:376
msgid "LLVM dialect -- machine-near IR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:378
msgid ""
"The LLVM dialect models LLVM IR as pliron operations, providing a 1:1 "
"mapping to textual `.ll` files. Its modeling lives upstream in the `pliron-"
"llvm` crate; cuda-oxide re-exports it (and adds the textual exporter) "
"through the `llvm-export` crate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:383
msgid ""
"**Arithmetic and casts**: all 19 LLVM binary ops (`llvm.add` through `llvm."
"frem`), plus 13 cast ops (`llvm.sext`, `llvm.trunc`, `llvm.bitcast`, ...)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:385
msgid ""
"**Control flow**: `llvm.br`, `llvm.cond_br`, `llvm.switch`, `llvm.return`, "
"`llvm.unreachable` -- with block arguments translated to PHI nodes on export."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:387
msgid ""
"**Textual export**: the `llvm_export::export` module emits valid LLVM IR "
"text, including `@llvm.used` arrays and `!nvvm.annotations` metadata for GPU "
"kernels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:390
msgid "dialect-nvvm -- GPU intrinsics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:392
msgid ""
"`dialect-nvvm` wraps LLVM's NVPTX backend intrinsics as typed pliron "
"operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:395
msgid ""
"**Thread indexing**: `nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x`, `nvvm."
"read_ptx_sreg_ctaid_x`, `nvvm.barrier0` -- the building blocks of `thread::"
"index_1d()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:397
msgid ""
"**Warp-level primitives**: shuffle (`nvvm.shfl_sync`), vote, and reduce "
"operations for warp-cooperative algorithms."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:399
msgid ""
"**Accelerator ops**: TMA bulk copies, WGMMA matrix multiply-accumulate "
"(Hopper), and tcgen05 tensor core operations (Blackwell) -- the hardware "
"instructions behind the [Advanced GPU Features](../advanced/tensor-memory-"
"accelerator.md) chapters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/pliron.md:404
msgid ""
"Each dialect is covered in detail in [Pliron Dialects](mlir-dialects.md)."
msgstr ""
